<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec4.p3" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec4.p3"></a><p>The method of steepest descent in a Matlab program was used to adjust the enzyme and nucleotide-sugar concentrations that give rise to a mixture of terminal glycans of a specified pattern. Specifically, in the initial evaluation of the model the enzyme and nucleotide-sugar concentrations that produce the terminal glycans in the same order of magnitude were used as listed in <a href="#pone-0000713-t003">Table 3</a>. Later in the study the method was applied to search conditions that will produce a single terminal N-glycan. The objective function that was minimized is shown in Eq. 6, where <span class="inline-formula"><img src="/article/fetchObject.action?uri=info:doi/10.1371/journal.pone.0000713.e023&amp;representation=PNG" class="inline-graphic"></span> is the concentration of glycan species g<sub>i</sub> in compartment n predicted at each iteration of the solver, and <span class="inline-formula"><img src="/article/fetchObject.action?uri=info:doi/10.1371/journal.pone.0000713.e024&amp;representation=PNG" class="inline-graphic"></span> is the desired value.<a name="" id=""></a><span class="equation"><img src="/article/fetchObject.action?uri=info:doi/10.1371/journal.pone.0000713.e025&amp;representation=PNG" class="inline-graphic"><span class="note">(Eq.6)</span></span><br>The enzyme and nucleotide-sugar concentrations obtained were values of a local minimum of the objective function, not a global minimum. Nevertheless, these values enable us to better discern the changes of various fluxes under different simulation conditions.</p>
